Gabara’s comment: Your analogy confuses the method with the content. The "weight" of the knowledge—the physics law, the medical fact—doesn't change. Using football, for example, isn't taking weight off the bar; it's teaching proper form and providing motivation so the student doesn't quit the gym.
The struggle should be in mastering the complex subject, not in enduring a boring delivery. If an engaging method teaches the same rigorous content, it doesn't make education easier; it makes it more effective. The goal is real, retained knowledge, and that's what this builds.

share_info.desc: manda | Key Footsteps Music’s comment: Real learning is not memorizing facts. Real learning is understanding the concepts and facts in their true context. When you make things relatable to something the learner already understands, the learner takes in the information for real (not just enough to regurgitate them on a test) and owns it for life. This tool makes things much more doable. Children don't generally have the life experience to be able to do that on their own. Most text books are incredibly dry and boring because they're not relevant to anything the learner already understands in life. Virtue signal all you want about the evils of big corporations, but this application of the technology is actually very helpful and aligns with how our minds learn. Those who are successful in things like med school or law school usually learn ways to put the text into personal context and how to study in more efficient ways than what they're taught at the high school level.

share_info.desc:
Gabara’s comment: Bro, this isn't rocket science. Let's say a kid doesn't understand why 1+1=2. By your logic, he should just memorize it because it's an obvious fact. But if he doesn't understand the why, how is he supposed to know what 1999+1111 is?
So how do you explain it to him? You use something easy, like counting fingers. You show him one finger plus another finger equals two. But what if that doesn't interest him? So you use what he loves—his toy dinosaurs. 'Look, one dinosaur meets another dinosaur, now there are two!'
That simple, interesting example makes him get it and remember it way better. This is the exact same thing I'm talking about.
I could just tell you the dry theory, and you might not get it—which is what happens to millions of students. Using something they're interested in lights up their brain. It's not cheating; it's creating a kind of 'photographic memory' for the concept because it's tied to something they enjoy and understand. The information isn't easier; the path to it is clearer.

Because having the best educational institutions sounds impressive, but if you look who can afford it and how few people have access to that elite education, it shows clearly the systematic problem. Focussing on good education for few who can afford it, while the majority gets barely any decent education. The US school system is known for being not good. Instead of teaching history, they teach propaganda. They have multiple choice tests and the literacy rate it going down for years. That’s a crisis of education. And that for a rich country like the US. In Germany the public education is decent. The average university is also good. People can study at a totally average institution and they can be certain to receive a high quality education. So I don‘t really see how your point is relevant here.

Things Everyone Should Know’s comment: Studies show Americans are generally worse at geography than the British.
National Geographic found only 37% of young Americans could find Iraq on a map, and half couldn’t even locate New York State
In similar UK tests, Brits scored higher, especially on Europe and the Middle East.
It’s mostly because US schools blend geography into “social studies,” while in the UK it’s taught as a separate subject, so they just get more practice
So yeah… the stereotype kinda checks out

share_info.desc: 🪲 with a big 🫏’s comment: Reading comprehension requires being able to accurately distinguish between different voices and motivations in texts which means understanding subtext. If you can't do that you can't read. When you have a text that is meant to manipulate you; youre reading propaganda it's not educational. Who decides what is left out for you is who decides whose voices are left out. This is removing subtext. It is the difference between reading a book and reading a summary. You can't learn by reading a summary; you can only pretend you've learned in a superficial way that falls apart the minute you need to know something beyond the summary. Educations purpose is to challenge people; that is how you grow. If you say lets take all the weights off the machines and write 100kg on it so everyone can feel strong; it doesn't make anyone actually strong; it makes everyone weak and delulu. When someone asks you to actually lift the 100kg you will say sure I do that all time; fail and break your back. share_info.desc: RevyExt’s comment: Assuming the teacher is approaching every student individually, which in most cases isn't. In my country school is also free and available for everyone, but the teachers mostly just follow the curriculum, giving basic explanations and assigning homework. Skilled teachers that are willing to sacrifice their time in order to better their students are far and between. In which case if most of your staff are lazy teachers that can't properly impart their knowledge, then what's the point of having them and paying them salaries if they can't do their job right?

share_info.desc: 1StepBack,2StepsForward’s comment: Like all things new, it takes time for society to adapt. Technology is advancing at a rate at which it will outrun our capacity to adapt. We haven't yet truly evaluated the effects of social media, cigarettes had a century before society finally called it out for what it was. A cancer. And in our hands we have the most powerful source of propaganda the world has ever seen. And we're making sure they "regulate" social media, but, the truth is, we don't know what it's really there for. You'd wonder why the US needs to own the biggest sources of social media and communication and all else is banned in their country... Oh but enough social media conspiracy we're on to AI now, the next big thing! But we don't know what the effects of instant communication have been in our society, let alone the addictive side of it! Yes but AI is the next big thing, and it will carry us into the future. Wait a minute so you want us to keep going knowing we haven't even stopped to analyze our situation? Yes, society will reach a point in which it will have to decide between making sure this technology does good for us and our offspring, or bow down and ask for our dopamine hits like the good boys we are. But like everything in an overwhelming capitalist system we have been bombarded with nothing but innovation and comfort products that keep us satisfied and unwilling to question, because our minds want all the benefits and none of the consequences and as long as we pretend there are no consequences, there are only benefits. I think pretty soon, those that have any glimpse of self awareness and just a tiny bit of fear for what's to come, will come to consider joining the amish, or creating a 21st century version of it anyways.

Over 3,775 free Black individuals owned more than 12,000 slaves by 1830, according to U.S. census records. One of the earliest legal cases establishing lifelong slavery involved Anthony Johnson, a free Black man in Virginia, who in 1655 sued to keep John Casor, another Black man, as a slave for life. The court ruled in Johnson’s favor, setting a precedent for chattel slavery in the colonies.
Another example of racial cooperation was Bacon’s Rebellion in 1676, where poor white and Black individuals united against the colonial elite. They burned Jamestown and nearly overthrew the government. In response, the ruling class hardened racial divisions to prevent future uprisings. At the height of slavery, only about 1.4% of white Americans owned slaves. Some Black slaveholders also owned white indentured servants alongside Black slaves.
The North was just as brutal as the South, if not more so. Southern slaveholders had a financial incentive to keep slaves alive and working, while Northern industrialists often subjected workers to dangerous conditions, starvation wages, and violent retaliation for organizing or striking. History has been taught in a way that divides people, hiding the fact that poor whites and Blacks once fought side by side—and could again.
